&gt;&gt; What Frank is referring to is more properly termed a &quot;Pseudo-Skeptic&quot;.
&gt;&gt;  Indeed Skepticism is a vital part of scientific investigations, but it&#39;s
&gt;&gt; Skepticism based on consideration of the facts and  expressing a caution or
&gt;&gt; difference of opinion is what is useful in the Scientific community.  A
&gt;&gt; pseudo Skeptic is characterized by a person who clearly does not know the
&gt;&gt; subject area other than through what may be termed &quot;common knowledge&quot; or, at
&gt;&gt; best, a brief overview of the literature.  A  Pseudo skeptic&#39;s &quot;opinions&quot;
&gt;&gt; are based primarily on an emotional attitude towards the subject matter
&gt;&gt; rather than what few &quot;facts&quot; he knows.  Its a psychological defense he uses
&gt;&gt; to shore up his status, the validity of his work, and to cope with things
&gt;&gt; that frighten him.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; A real Skeptic is a friend with a difference of opinion based on a genuine
&gt;&gt; desire to help and sufficient data on the subject at hand to know what
&gt;&gt; he/she is talking about.  We, as Scientists must always have a health dose
&gt;&gt; of real Skepticism.  Otherwise we risk being the exact inverse of the Pseudo
&gt;&gt; skeptic---the &quot;FLAKE&quot;.  The Flake is the type who will believe anything.
&gt;&gt;  Just as the Pseudo Skeptic has a need to reject things on emotional
&gt;&gt; grounds, the Flake has a need to accept EVERYTHING on emotional grounds.
&gt;&gt;  Any shadow,  sound, or corner of the eye flash just HAS to be a ghost or
&gt;&gt; spirit. ----or whatever.  I think you know the type, and   these &quot;flakes&quot;
&gt;&gt; are what Pseudo skeptics accuse us who are serious about paranormal studies
&gt;&gt;  of being.  Perhaps its one of the reasons they get us so angry.
&gt;&gt;
